                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Thomas Liddington, and lodge in Phoenix-place, Old-street. On the 21st of November I went to Mrs. Walker's, and left my pattens there - when I called again they were gone.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-270-person2047">
                  MARY 
                  WALKER
               <interp inst="t18311201-270-person2047" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-270-person2047" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-270-person2047" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep the house - Donalds lodged there. On the 21st he came down, and put his coat into the drawer as usual - the next morning I heard a quarrel up stairs about missing some things; I then opened the drawer, and missed the coat - I went up, and said, "What have you done with the coat?" Donalds said, "I put it into the drawer;" they then came down, and the prisoner said, "Never mind; I took it - I will make it all right on Saturday night."</p>
               <p>
            
